Example \(\PageIndex{3}\) Find the vertex of the quadratic \(f(x)=2x^{2} -6x+7\). Rewrite the quadratic into transformation form (vertex form). Solution The horizontal coordinate of the vertex will be at \[h=-\dfrac{b}{2a} =-\dfrac{-6}{2(2)} =\dfrac{6}{4} =\dfrac{3}{2} 
onumber\] The vertical coordinate of the vertex will be at \[f(\dfrac{3}{2} )=2(\dfrac{3}{2})^{2} -6(\dfrac{3}{2} )+7=\dfrac{5}{2} 
onumber\] Rewriting into transformation form, the stretch factor will be the same as the \(a\) in the original quadratic. Using the vertex to determine the shifts, \[f(x)=2(x-\dfrac{3}{2} )^{2} +\dfrac{5}{2} 
onumber\]

